WEBVTT

00:01.871 --> 00:03.438
[Claire] Previously...

00:03.568 --> 00:04.787
There's a face I never
thought I'd see again.

00:04.917 --> 00:06.484
Tom Christie.

00:06.571 --> 00:09.531
[Tom] This is my son, Allan,
and my daughter, Malva.

00:09.661 --> 00:12.273
You're not harboring
one of those rebels, are ye?

00:12.403 --> 00:13.970
Ahh!

00:14.101 --> 00:15.363
[Jamie] It is between
me and him.

00:15.493 --> 00:17.017
I canna let him do it.
I'll be your Indian agent.

00:17.147 --> 00:20.368
Well, I come from the future.

00:20.455 --> 00:21.543
200 years from now.

00:21.673 --> 00:23.023
[Young Ian] And ye?

00:23.545 --> 00:25.025
You ken all this time, Uncle?

00:25.155 --> 00:26.678
Not many people
would understand,

00:26.765 --> 00:28.854
so we kept it
between ourselves.

00:28.985 --> 00:30.813
A man must surely build
a house for God

00:30.943 --> 00:32.815
before building
a home for himself.

00:32.945 --> 00:34.860
Aye, well,
we don't have a church yet.

00:34.991 --> 00:37.776
I've recreated anesthetic.

00:37.907 --> 00:39.300
Well, it's called ether.

00:39.387 --> 00:41.476
And it sends you to sleep?

00:41.606 --> 00:42.999
[Claire] Something deeper
than sleep.

00:43.130 --> 00:45.828
[dramatic music plays]

00:50.963 --> 00:53.662
[soft string music plays]

00:53.836 --> 00:56.621
♪ ♪

00:57.709 --> 00:58.928
Osiyo, ginalii.

01:04.325 --> 01:05.195
[Still Water] Osiyo, ginalii.

01:30.612 --> 01:32.179
We want more guns.

01:34.355 --> 01:36.357
Who doesna?

01:36.487 --> 01:37.532
Who indeed?

01:39.360 --> 01:41.144
You're here
on King George's behalf.

01:43.190 --> 01:46.628
You tell him this:
we want more weapons--

01:46.758 --> 01:50.153
rifles, muskets, guns.

01:54.331 --> 01:56.028
So what do you have
to say on the matter?

02:01.251 --> 02:04.776
I say trade goods are certain.

02:04.907 --> 02:08.780
Knives... likely.

02:08.867 --> 02:10.869
Guns are a different matter.

02:10.956 --> 02:14.221
[speaking Cherokee]

02:14.308 --> 02:16.484
You must understand,

02:16.571 --> 02:18.877
the king may be hesitant
to arm you

02:19.008 --> 02:20.357
against his own people.

02:20.488 --> 02:23.273
You must understand

02:23.404 --> 02:25.319
that we can kill them
without guns,

02:25.449 --> 02:27.451
if we want to.

02:27.582 --> 02:29.758
Of course ye can.

02:29.888 --> 02:31.542
But you are wise enough not to.

02:32.848 --> 02:34.458
Not yet.

02:37.244 --> 02:39.115
I like you, Bear-Killer.

02:39.246 --> 02:40.160
You're a funny man.

02:42.423 --> 02:44.599
Maybe. Give it time.

02:44.729 --> 02:47.254
Perhaps you have forgotten,

02:47.384 --> 02:50.126
the Cherokee have fought
with the king before,

02:50.213 --> 02:52.781
and we may choose to fight
with him again,

02:52.911 --> 02:55.653
if the time comes.

02:55.784 --> 02:58.917
But that is a decision
for another day,

02:59.004 --> 03:01.050
because our war is with those
who cross the treaty line.

03:02.791 --> 03:05.924
They build houses, plant crops,

03:06.055 --> 03:08.275
take game
from our hunting grounds.

03:08.362 --> 03:10.015
If the king
cannot keep his people

03:10.146 --> 03:12.496
where they belong,

03:12.627 --> 03:16.283
how can he protest
when we defend our land?

03:16.413 --> 03:18.633
So, Bear-Killer,

03:18.763 --> 03:20.156
you will tell
the king these things?

03:28.338 --> 03:30.253
I'll consider it, certainly.

03:31.733 --> 03:32.908
Hm.

03:34.388 --> 03:35.911
It's only that...

03:40.220 --> 03:42.222
...I canna promise it.

03:44.833 --> 03:47.836
Wado.Thank you.

03:47.966 --> 03:49.881
For your honestly, at least.

03:52.623 --> 03:54.059
I hope you'll stay the night.

03:58.803 --> 04:00.979
[man] ♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:01.153 --> 04:04.069
♪ Of a lad that is gone ♪

04:04.244 --> 04:06.507
♪ Say, could that lad ♪

04:06.681 --> 04:09.466
♪ Be I? ♪

04:09.640 --> 04:11.860
♪ Merry of soul ♪

04:11.947 --> 04:14.689
♪ He sailed on a day ♪

04:14.863 --> 04:17.039
♪ Over the sea ♪

04:17.126 --> 04:20.129
♪ To Skye ♪

04:20.303 --> 04:22.697
[woman] ♪ Billow and breeze ♪

04:22.784 --> 04:25.221
♪ Islands and seas ♪

04:25.395 --> 04:31.096
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

04:31.271 --> 04:33.142
-[man] ♪ All that was good ♪
-[woman] ♪ All that was good ♪

04:33.316 --> 04:35.666
[man] ♪ All that was fair ♪

04:35.840 --> 04:37.842
[both] ♪ All that was me ♪

04:38.016 --> 04:40.845
♪ Is gone ♪

04:41.019 --> 04:43.152
♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:43.326 --> 04:46.111
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

04:46.286 --> 04:48.331
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

04:48.418 --> 04:51.247
♪ Be I? ♪

04:51.421 --> 04:53.423
♪ Merry of soul ♪

04:53.597 --> 04:56.470
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

04:56.644 --> 05:00.474
♪ Over the sea ♪

05:00.648 --> 05:06.654
♪ To Skye ♪

05:07.132 --> 05:10.005
[dramatic music plays]

05:10.092 --> 05:12.877
♪ ♪

05:14.966 --> 05:17.752
[man singing in Gaelic]

05:17.839 --> 05:20.624
♪ ♪

05:31.243 --> 05:34.072
[hammering]

05:49.827 --> 05:50.915
[Malva] Does it hurt?

05:53.657 --> 05:56.530
[Claire] Well, I shouldn't think
so.

05:56.617 --> 05:58.358
There.
The wound has almost healed.

06:00.272 --> 06:02.449
There.

06:02.536 --> 06:05.147
That should be back
to normal in a week or two.

06:05.277 --> 06:07.715
Then we can see about mending
that right hand of yours.

06:07.845 --> 06:10.631
Well, I've decided that I shall
leave this hand as it is.

06:10.761 --> 06:12.763
Why?

06:12.894 --> 06:15.679
If this infirmity
be God's will,

06:15.810 --> 06:18.116
then so be it.

06:19.291 --> 06:22.164
Is it God's will that your goat
should injure her leg?

06:22.294 --> 06:25.515
'Cause if so, then you should
have left her to die

06:25.602 --> 06:28.039
instead of having me mend it.

06:28.126 --> 06:31.086
Do you think God regards you
as less deserving

06:31.173 --> 06:33.393
than your goat?

06:33.523 --> 06:36.352
Now, I shouldn't think so,
given his famed regard

06:36.439 --> 06:38.398
for even
the smallest of sparrows.

06:38.528 --> 06:40.095
[Tom] Indeed.

06:40.225 --> 06:42.663
Then I'm sure you will be
familiar with the letter

06:42.793 --> 06:44.926
from St. Paul to Timothy
in which he says--

06:45.056 --> 06:47.319
"Let a woman learn in silence.

06:47.450 --> 06:49.191
"I suffer not a woman to teach,

06:49.321 --> 06:51.454
"nor to usurp authority
over the man,

06:51.585 --> 06:52.890
but to be in silence."

06:56.416 --> 06:59.549
Well, clearly,
St. Paul also met a woman

06:59.680 --> 07:01.464
he couldn't out-argue.

07:01.551 --> 07:03.945
No, no, better to put a stopper
on the entire sex

07:04.075 --> 07:05.990
than to win your point fairly.

07:06.121 --> 07:08.253
The devil finds work
for idle hands, Malva.

07:08.340 --> 07:09.429
Be off with you.

07:14.999 --> 07:18.002
You know, the truth
of the matter is...

07:18.089 --> 07:19.308
you're afraid.

07:19.439 --> 07:21.528
[chuckles] Afraid?

07:21.658 --> 07:23.399
Yes.

07:23.530 --> 07:25.053
You're afraid
that I will hurt you.

07:27.272 --> 07:30.754
Or that you'll lose
what use you have left

07:30.885 --> 07:32.756
of this hand now.

07:32.887 --> 07:35.063
But when I operate,

07:35.193 --> 07:37.674
I have a medicine called ether,

07:37.761 --> 07:39.633
and that can put you to sleep,

07:39.720 --> 07:41.591
so you won't feel a thing,
I promise.

07:43.898 --> 07:45.029
Thank you.

07:46.640 --> 07:47.989
But I've much to do today.

07:51.949 --> 07:54.691
[bright string music plays]

07:54.865 --> 07:56.171
♪ ♪

07:56.258 --> 07:57.259
[sighs]

07:59.914 --> 08:02.656
[metal scraping]

08:04.135 --> 08:06.007
How's your back?

08:06.616 --> 08:08.531
Much better,
Mistress Fraser.

08:08.618 --> 08:09.880
The salve you gave me helped.

08:10.011 --> 08:11.926
Good.

08:12.013 --> 08:13.884
Only yesterday we were saying
how remarkable it is

08:14.015 --> 08:16.278
that you're a physician,
you being a lady.

08:16.365 --> 08:19.107
-Weren't we, Allan?
-Yes, we were.

08:19.237 --> 08:21.326
Particularly
when others might accuse

08:21.457 --> 08:23.633
such a woman of witchcraft
and the like.

08:23.764 --> 08:26.114
Well, if I should need
to sharpen my broomstick

08:26.244 --> 08:28.203
or my surgeon's knives,
Mr. Christie,

08:28.333 --> 08:30.335
I'll come to you first.

08:30.466 --> 08:31.946
He doesn't take the slightest
bit of interest

08:32.076 --> 08:33.338
in the subject of healing,

08:33.425 --> 08:35.427
whereas I'm eager to learn.

08:36.385 --> 08:38.169
Well, if you'd like
to accompany me in the morning,

08:38.300 --> 08:39.867
my daughter Marsali's
with child,

08:39.997 --> 08:40.911
and I'm going to examine her.

08:41.042 --> 08:42.434
You might find it interesting.

08:42.565 --> 08:44.436
Malva has duties
to attend to at home.

08:47.004 --> 08:48.005
Well, perhaps another time.

08:49.137 --> 08:51.052
Yes.

08:51.182 --> 08:53.924
[somber music plays]

08:54.098 --> 08:56.797
♪ ♪

09:09.549 --> 09:12.290
[soft flute music plays]

09:12.464 --> 09:15.250
♪ ♪

09:41.189 --> 09:42.712
Hmm...

09:50.459 --> 09:51.286
Ian?

09:53.854 --> 09:55.072
[Young Ian] What is it, Uncle?

09:57.509 --> 09:59.599
There is a woman in my bed.

10:11.306 --> 10:13.700
[Young Ian] There's...
two of them, Uncle.

10:13.830 --> 10:15.615
And the other one's
waiting her turn.

10:16.877 --> 10:18.269
Two of them?

10:18.400 --> 10:19.619
What do they think I am?

10:21.316 --> 10:22.926
Christ!

10:23.057 --> 10:25.059
No, Uncle,
they dinna think ye're Him.

10:25.189 --> 10:27.757
They ken ye're
the king's agent.

10:27.888 --> 10:30.760
Suppose they think
it's an honor

10:30.891 --> 10:32.588
and a privilege to--

10:32.719 --> 10:34.634
Madam, cease.

10:34.764 --> 10:36.940
The two of you.

10:37.071 --> 10:40.291
You're very beautiful,
but, uh, I canna lie with you.

10:40.422 --> 10:42.816
[speaking Cherokee]

10:42.903 --> 10:45.688
She says she wants
to know why not.

10:45.819 --> 10:48.038
Tell them I have
an oath over me,

10:48.169 --> 10:50.432
and, well, I s--I swore--
I've--

10:50.562 --> 10:53.087
I've sworn fidelity to my wife.

10:57.265 --> 10:58.788
[Young Ian] They dinna seem
to care so much.

10:58.919 --> 11:00.616
[Jamie] No.

11:00.703 --> 11:02.662
Well, give them an excuse,
and tell them to cover up.

11:05.360 --> 11:07.449
[grunts] I'll try.

11:08.058 --> 11:10.234
But it is Mohawk I speak.

11:10.321 --> 11:11.845
Hardly any Cherokee.

11:11.932 --> 11:13.411
Well, try, please.

11:13.934 --> 11:15.109
All right, all right.

11:15.239 --> 11:17.459
Um...

11:17.589 --> 11:20.244
[speaking Cherokee]

11:24.422 --> 11:25.946
[chuckles]

11:26.076 --> 11:27.904
-Watali.
-[women giggle]

11:28.035 --> 11:30.690
[speaking Cherokee]

11:36.696 --> 11:39.133
Uh, I-I told them that the, uh,

11:39.263 --> 11:41.178
the Creator came to you
in a dream

11:41.309 --> 11:43.659
and instructed you that
you mustn't lie with a woman

11:43.790 --> 11:45.835
until you've brought guns
to Chief Bird.

11:45.922 --> 11:47.010
Well, at least I hope I did.

11:47.141 --> 11:48.795
Until I what?

11:48.882 --> 11:50.797
It's the best I could
think of in a hurry, Uncle.

11:50.927 --> 11:53.887
[speaking Cherokee]

11:55.584 --> 11:58.369
[speaking Cherokee]

12:00.023 --> 12:01.982
[laughs]

12:02.112 --> 12:03.766
[laughter]

12:03.853 --> 12:06.116
One of the lasses, well,

12:06.247 --> 12:08.597
she's disappointed,

12:08.728 --> 12:11.078
because you have
a verra nice, um...

12:12.906 --> 12:14.211
And the--the other,

12:14.342 --> 12:16.648
she's a little more
philosophical.

12:16.779 --> 12:18.825
She says she might have
borne ye children,

12:18.912 --> 12:21.349
but they might have had
red hair, I think.

12:21.479 --> 12:22.872
What's wrong with red hair?

12:23.003 --> 12:25.353
I gather it isna somethin'
ye want yer bairn

12:25.483 --> 12:27.181
to be marked with,
if ye can help it.

12:27.311 --> 12:29.096
There's no danger of that
happening now, is there?

12:29.226 --> 12:30.662
Thank you.

12:30.750 --> 12:32.360
Wado.

12:47.505 --> 12:49.507
Ye'd be advised
to stifle yer glee.

12:49.638 --> 12:52.075
[laughs]

12:52.206 --> 12:54.991
[soft music plays]

12:55.165 --> 12:57.124
♪ ♪

12:57.211 --> 12:58.647
[Germain] Avast, ye scoundrels!

12:58.734 --> 12:59.866
Into the wind we go!

12:59.953 --> 13:01.519
Your money or your life.

13:01.606 --> 13:04.696
♪ ♪

13:04.784 --> 13:06.524
What are they doing out there?

13:06.655 --> 13:08.396
One day,
'tis highway robbers,

13:08.526 --> 13:11.312
the next it's sailors,
or worse, pirates.

13:13.749 --> 13:15.403
Give no quarter!

13:21.931 --> 13:23.106
I'll get it.

13:25.239 --> 13:26.588
Sorry. I did knock, but--

13:26.718 --> 13:27.807
Oh, Malva, come in.

13:31.332 --> 13:33.029
I wasn't expecting you.

13:33.116 --> 13:35.031
I was able to finish
all my chores.

13:35.553 --> 13:37.207
Marsali, you don't mind,
do you?

13:37.338 --> 13:39.601
I invited Miss Christie
to come and observe.

13:39.731 --> 13:43.126
Well, let this be a lesson
to ye, lass.

13:43.257 --> 13:44.301
If you do have
the misfortune to marry,

13:44.432 --> 13:45.825
dinna let them touch ye,

13:45.912 --> 13:47.348
or else you'll
end up like this.

13:48.044 --> 13:50.960
Here, I'm examining the stomach

13:51.091 --> 13:53.093
to make sure the baby
is in the right place.

13:53.180 --> 13:55.312
With time and practice,
you can feel when the baby

13:55.399 --> 13:56.792
is in the proper position--

13:56.879 --> 13:59.229
head down, towards the pelvis.

13:59.360 --> 14:00.796
It seems to me
the proper position

14:00.927 --> 14:02.145
would be out of my womb.

14:02.276 --> 14:04.060
I agree with you.

14:04.887 --> 14:06.933
But everything--
everything feels good.

14:08.978 --> 14:10.240
Now I'm going to check
Marsali's pulse.

14:15.332 --> 14:17.595
And you do that by...

14:17.726 --> 14:19.728
locating the blood vessel
below the thumb.

14:19.815 --> 14:20.860
Take your two fingers.

14:24.080 --> 14:25.603
Feel the pulsing?

14:25.734 --> 14:27.083
Yes.

14:27.214 --> 14:28.258
We can count that.

14:31.479 --> 14:34.961
We count the heartbeat until
the minute glass runs out.

14:35.091 --> 14:36.136
Here.

14:41.358 --> 14:43.534
And anywhere from 60 to 70,

14:43.665 --> 14:46.320
even up to 100 beats per minute
is quite normal.

14:46.450 --> 14:47.234
-[children shouting]
-[object shatters]

14:47.364 --> 14:48.713
Quiet, Germain!

14:48.844 --> 14:50.280
Or I will smack your bottom

14:50.411 --> 14:52.021
so ye'll no' sit
'til the sabbath--

14:52.152 --> 14:54.328
[children shouting, laughing]

14:56.460 --> 14:58.114
Malva, would you mind
taking the children

14:58.245 --> 14:59.942
outside again for a bit?

15:00.073 --> 15:01.204
Of course, Mistress Fraser.

15:02.945 --> 15:04.555
Come, children.
Let your ma rest.

15:07.689 --> 15:08.951
I'm at my wit's end with him.

15:10.518 --> 15:12.520
Where is Fergus?

15:12.650 --> 15:14.478
Shouldn't he be helping you?

15:14.609 --> 15:16.089
Oh, aye.

15:16.176 --> 15:19.266
Believe me,
Fergus is their first mate.

15:21.703 --> 15:23.139
Is everything all right
between the two of you?

15:24.836 --> 15:26.490
I've noticed
some more bruising.

15:27.535 --> 15:31.278
Ah, no, I fell is all.

15:31.408 --> 15:33.367
Chasing after Germain,
of course.

15:37.197 --> 15:39.416
[Claire] And you've had
no spotting?

15:39.547 --> 15:40.809
Or bleeding, I mean.

15:40.896 --> 15:42.680
No. None.

15:42.811 --> 15:44.334
But my head aches most days,

15:44.465 --> 15:47.859
and my feet feel
as heavy as lead.

15:49.470 --> 15:53.213
I have noticed some slight
swelling in your ankles.

15:53.343 --> 15:54.954
What does--what does it mean?

15:57.434 --> 15:59.436
It's probably nothing.

15:59.523 --> 16:01.438
But I do think you should
come up to the big house

16:01.569 --> 16:03.049
and stay with us,

16:03.179 --> 16:04.267
so I can keep
a closer eye on you.

16:08.358 --> 16:09.359
Marsali...

16:12.536 --> 16:15.409
...I have to ask,
for the sake of the baby...

16:18.368 --> 16:20.370
...where did those bruises
come from?

16:20.501 --> 16:22.633
Did Fergus hurt you?

16:22.720 --> 16:24.374
It's no secret
that he's been drinking

16:24.505 --> 16:25.723
more than usual lately.

16:28.770 --> 16:29.684
It wasna his fault.

16:32.034 --> 16:33.035
[sighs]

16:34.428 --> 16:36.908
He did... grab my arm...

16:41.130 --> 16:42.479
...only because
I went after him

16:42.610 --> 16:43.437
wi' a posser.

16:48.094 --> 16:50.922
I am cursed
with my mother's temper,

16:51.053 --> 16:53.055
and it got the better of me.

16:55.231 --> 16:56.972
So he was defending himself?

16:59.279 --> 17:00.802
Uh...

17:00.932 --> 17:02.847
Just--

17:02.978 --> 17:07.330
I was so tired of him...

17:07.461 --> 17:11.073
being gone, being drunk.

17:13.641 --> 17:15.860
[sighs]

17:15.991 --> 17:18.037
If only we could get
to the bottom of...

17:18.167 --> 17:19.864
what's been troubling him.

17:19.995 --> 17:20.952
[Marsali] I ken
what's troubling him!

17:22.171 --> 17:25.174
He's ashamed, the fool.

17:25.305 --> 17:28.177
[somber music plays]

17:28.308 --> 17:31.006
He's taken a notion...

17:31.137 --> 17:33.965
that he should have been there
to defend us

17:34.096 --> 17:37.404
when what happened
with that...

17:37.491 --> 17:39.145
bastard, Lionel.

17:42.191 --> 17:43.410
That wasn't his fault.

17:45.064 --> 17:47.675
I've said that
time and time again.

17:47.805 --> 17:49.764
How could it be his fault
when he wasna there?

17:49.851 --> 17:50.895
But he willna hear it.

17:52.462 --> 17:54.203
He thinks
I shouldna been there.

17:54.334 --> 17:55.552
Working.

17:57.815 --> 17:59.687
[sighs]
Look at me, going to pieces.

17:59.817 --> 18:01.341
Sorry.

18:01.515 --> 18:04.779
♪ ♪

18:04.866 --> 18:08.043
It was nothing compared
to what happened to you.

18:13.570 --> 18:15.616
I'm sorry.
I didna mean to upset ye.

18:16.878 --> 18:18.706
No.

18:18.793 --> 18:20.882
It's, um...

18:21.012 --> 18:23.145
oh, it's just...

18:23.276 --> 18:24.886
I think I have a headache
coming on, that's all.

18:25.060 --> 18:27.802
♪ ♪

18:35.853 --> 18:38.421
[crows cawing]

18:50.651 --> 18:51.739
[Lionel] Dr. Rawlings.

18:51.869 --> 18:53.132
[Claire gasps]

18:55.917 --> 18:58.789
[breathing heavily]

18:58.920 --> 19:01.618
[tense music plays]

19:01.792 --> 19:04.578
♪ ♪

19:19.027 --> 19:21.725
[breathing frantically]

19:29.255 --> 19:30.908
[breathing slows]

19:40.266 --> 19:42.050
[Lizzie] Careful. Careful.
Ooh, careful.

19:42.181 --> 19:45.053
[soft music plays]

19:45.140 --> 19:47.011
♪ ♪

19:47.142 --> 19:48.665
Whoa! [laughs]

20:11.949 --> 20:13.734
What's that?

20:13.864 --> 20:15.257
[Brianna] White phosphorous.

20:15.344 --> 20:16.693
Present from Lord John.

20:18.304 --> 20:20.175
Isn't that explosive?

20:20.306 --> 20:21.307
[Brianna] No.

20:22.830 --> 20:25.441
White phosphorous
doesn't explode,

20:25.572 --> 20:29.184
but it does burst into flame
the minute it's exposed to air.

20:29.315 --> 20:30.620
That's why
it's packed in water.

20:32.100 --> 20:33.188
Is that all?

20:34.798 --> 20:36.974
Jemmy's with Lizzie, I hope.

20:37.105 --> 20:38.628
Yes.

20:38.759 --> 20:40.456
I'm going to make matches.

20:40.587 --> 20:43.590
I know how, in theory.
And I'll be careful, promise.

20:48.856 --> 20:49.900
I just spoke to Tom Christie.

20:51.815 --> 20:53.817
Hiram Crombie's
mother-in-law died.

20:53.948 --> 20:55.079
How sad.

20:56.951 --> 20:58.431
I'm sure the journey here
didn't help.

20:58.561 --> 21:00.302
Hiram wants a quick funeral.

21:00.433 --> 21:02.826
Tom's asked me to do it, since
their minister's been delayed.

21:02.957 --> 21:04.001
You know what
you'll preach about?

21:04.132 --> 21:05.307
[laughs]

21:05.438 --> 21:07.483
I have absolutely no idea.

21:08.310 --> 21:09.659
I suppose I'll have
to pray about it.

21:12.358 --> 21:13.794
[Brianna] Well, hopefully
it's just the once,

21:13.924 --> 21:15.099
before their minister arrives.

21:15.839 --> 21:17.928
For now...

21:18.015 --> 21:19.321
I think
I'd better do this outside.

21:20.844 --> 21:23.456
[lively string music plays]

21:23.630 --> 21:26.415
♪ ♪

21:40.995 --> 21:42.213
[Jamie] Sassenach!

21:47.741 --> 21:48.698
Claire!

21:48.872 --> 21:51.658
♪ ♪

21:57.359 --> 21:58.621
[Mrs. Bug] Welcome home,
Mr. Fraser.

21:59.622 --> 22:00.623
Oh!

22:00.754 --> 22:01.711
[Jamie] Claire!

22:07.151 --> 22:09.284
You're back early.

22:09.415 --> 22:10.546
How was your visit
with the Cherokee?

22:12.287 --> 22:14.463
I missed you, Sassenach.

22:14.594 --> 22:15.638
I must have ye.

22:15.725 --> 22:16.944
[giggles]

22:17.074 --> 22:18.685
What? Now?

22:18.772 --> 22:20.730
Aye.

22:20.861 --> 22:22.036
Did I not tell ye
I've missed ye?

22:22.166 --> 22:23.254
[Claire] You just did.

22:23.429 --> 22:26.214
♪ ♪

22:27.302 --> 22:28.825
[moans]

22:28.956 --> 22:30.914
Just so we're clear,

22:31.045 --> 22:32.829
why don't you show me
exactly what you mean?

22:32.960 --> 22:34.788
[both moaning]

22:46.452 --> 22:48.105
[rumbling]

22:48.192 --> 22:49.324
[Claire laughs]

22:50.630 --> 22:52.719
[both chuckle]

22:52.849 --> 22:54.373
Mm, you're smiling.

22:54.460 --> 22:56.287
Nice, was it?

22:56.418 --> 22:58.159
Actually...

22:58.289 --> 23:00.814
I was trying
to rank your words--

23:00.944 --> 23:04.165
"I like you," "I love you,"

23:04.252 --> 23:07.081
"I worship you,"

23:07.211 --> 23:09.997
"I must have my cock
inside you"--

23:10.127 --> 23:12.565
in terms of
the relative sincerity.

23:12.695 --> 23:14.436
Oh, I meant every word of it.

23:14.523 --> 23:16.046
Especially the last one.

23:16.395 --> 23:18.179
Especially the last one.

23:18.309 --> 23:19.528
[both chuckle]

23:21.312 --> 23:23.880
Mm, the flesh requires
a bite to eat

23:24.011 --> 23:26.535
and a wee rest before
I can think of doing it again,

23:26.666 --> 23:29.408
but... the spirit
is always willing.

23:29.538 --> 23:30.887
[Claire chuckles]

23:34.848 --> 23:37.590
You're lucky you're married
to an auldman, Sassenach.

23:37.720 --> 23:38.765
Or I'd have you on your knees

23:38.895 --> 23:40.375
with your ass in the air
this minute.

23:40.506 --> 23:42.682
[both chuckle]

23:42.812 --> 23:44.814
Aw, I'm happy you missed me.

23:46.599 --> 23:47.817
I missed you too.

23:54.345 --> 23:55.390
I want to ask you something.

23:57.958 --> 24:00.134
But uh...

24:00.221 --> 24:03.442
every time I ask you
about the future,

24:03.572 --> 24:05.008
the answer is--

24:05.139 --> 24:06.401
Not to your liking?

24:08.011 --> 24:09.752
I can't promise anything,
but go ahead.

24:12.799 --> 24:14.714
In the coming war,

24:14.844 --> 24:17.368
do you remember from your books

24:17.499 --> 24:20.241
if the Cherokee side with
the loyalists or the rebels?

24:21.329 --> 24:23.853
I'm sorry.

24:23.984 --> 24:25.159
My knowledge
of American history

24:25.289 --> 24:27.161
isn't that extensive.

24:27.248 --> 24:28.292
Why?

24:31.165 --> 24:33.602
The war chief,
Bird Who Sings in the Morning,

24:33.733 --> 24:34.995
has requested weapons.

24:37.171 --> 24:40.914
And you're worried you might
be arming a potential enemy.

24:41.044 --> 24:44.483
Before I was appointed
Indian agent, uh,

24:44.613 --> 24:46.354
I would not question what a man
might need to defend himself.

24:46.441 --> 24:48.791
But...

24:48.922 --> 24:50.880
once again, I'm wrestling
with my conscience.

24:52.752 --> 24:55.102
And if you don't provide
them with weapons, then--

24:55.232 --> 24:57.321
Then they may decide to fight
alongside the rebels.

24:58.714 --> 25:00.716
With me.

25:00.847 --> 25:03.153
If I do give them guns,

25:03.240 --> 25:04.677
they'll likely fight
with the Crown.

25:06.635 --> 25:08.028
So they'll lose either way.

25:11.379 --> 25:13.512
Damned if you do
and damned if you don't.

25:16.427 --> 25:17.733
I know one thing.

25:20.214 --> 25:23.522
Richard Brown would have made
a terrible Indian agent.

25:26.176 --> 25:28.439
But you...

25:28.570 --> 25:30.833
I know that you'll do
the right thing.

25:34.968 --> 25:36.186
-[knock on door]
-[Young Ian] Uncle.

25:36.317 --> 25:37.013
Major MacDonald's coming.

25:40.582 --> 25:41.975
No rest for the weary.

25:51.724 --> 25:52.289
[MacDonald]
They haven't always been keen

25:52.376 --> 25:54.030
to parlay with us.

25:54.161 --> 25:56.467
Then again, they were with us
in the Tuscarora wars,

25:56.555 --> 25:58.557
between 1711 and 1714.

25:58.687 --> 25:59.601
Or was it 1715?

26:01.864 --> 26:04.258
Several prominent
Cherokee visited King George II

26:04.388 --> 26:06.129
some 40 or so years ago.

26:06.260 --> 26:08.654
And of course, they fought
with us against the French.

26:08.784 --> 26:11.482
That said...

26:11.613 --> 26:14.398
there was that trouble with
the Cherokee Rebellion in '58.

26:14.529 --> 26:16.052
[Jamie] Forgive me
for saying so, Major, but--

26:16.183 --> 26:18.577
Oh, my apologies.

26:19.795 --> 26:23.451
You asked one simple question
about past allegiances,

26:23.538 --> 26:25.627
and I bored you half to death
with my ramblings.

26:25.758 --> 26:28.935
Well, sometimes we get
a better idea of what's to come

26:29.065 --> 26:30.501
when we look at what's gone by.

26:32.242 --> 26:36.072
But, as I was going to say,

26:36.159 --> 26:39.772
in speaking wi' them...

26:39.902 --> 26:43.471
it seems they are undecided
as to what they want.

26:43.558 --> 26:45.342
[MacDonald] And what do you
think they want?

26:46.082 --> 26:47.606
It's more a question
of what they don't want.

26:49.695 --> 26:52.436
Settlers crossing
the western boundary.

26:52.567 --> 26:54.569
[sneezes] Oh.

26:54.700 --> 26:58.051
There's an expectation
the Crown will intervene,

26:58.181 --> 27:00.662
take a more aggressive stance.

27:01.707 --> 27:03.970
Are you suggesting
that we send soldiers?

27:04.100 --> 27:05.449
Not soldiers.

27:05.580 --> 27:06.886
Forgive me, Uncle.

27:07.016 --> 27:08.670
But they did say
what they wanted.

27:08.801 --> 27:09.889
-Ian.
-[sneezes]

27:10.019 --> 27:11.151
Ah, blast.

27:15.285 --> 27:16.896
Have you a cat, Colonel?

27:17.026 --> 27:19.028
Oh, aye.

27:19.159 --> 27:20.726
Yeah, wee Adso.

27:20.856 --> 27:22.031
Hiding somewhere hereabouts.

27:23.642 --> 27:25.165
The plight of the Indian--

27:25.295 --> 27:26.993
[sneezes] Ugh!

27:28.908 --> 27:31.301
Wretched creatures.

27:31.432 --> 27:33.260
I always seem to suffer
in their presence.

27:33.347 --> 27:35.654
-Indians?
-Cats.

27:35.784 --> 27:38.221
Although, some Indians as well.

27:38.352 --> 27:40.397
Oh. [blows nose]

27:40.528 --> 27:42.225
Forgive me,
I'm in need of some air.

27:42.356 --> 27:43.400
Will you excuse me?

27:45.751 --> 27:47.143
[sneezes] Ugh.

27:51.931 --> 27:53.236
Why did ye no' mention

27:53.367 --> 27:55.195
Chief Bird's request
for weapons?

27:55.325 --> 27:58.024
Because I decided against it.

27:58.154 --> 28:00.548
It's not your place to speak up
in front of the major.

28:00.635 --> 28:02.855
'Tis only that ye
told the chief.

28:02.985 --> 28:05.901
I promised him I'd consider
his request, nothing more.

28:08.469 --> 28:10.558
I spoke wi' yer auntie

28:10.689 --> 28:14.301
about who the Cherokee will
fight for in the coming war.

28:14.431 --> 28:17.043
She couldna say
wi' any certainty.

28:17.173 --> 28:19.872
But she has knowledge
of what will come to pass?

28:21.134 --> 28:25.007
The royal provinces will unite
to become a new nation.

28:25.138 --> 28:27.140
But they'll have no king.

28:27.270 --> 28:29.098
Claire is certain of that.

28:29.664 --> 28:31.100
Those loyal to the Crown
will lose?

28:31.231 --> 28:32.841
Aye.

28:32.972 --> 28:34.538
And us?

28:36.279 --> 28:38.673
Well, there will come a time

28:38.804 --> 28:42.068
when I will fight
alongside the rebels.

28:42.155 --> 28:44.244
They will win the war.

28:45.419 --> 28:48.683
But I dinna ken which side
the Cherokee will fight.

28:48.814 --> 28:50.990
Do ye see?

28:51.120 --> 28:53.775
If Chief Bird acquires weapons,
they may soon be pointed at us.

28:53.906 --> 28:56.125
[foreboding music plays]

28:56.299 --> 28:57.518
♪ ♪

28:57.648 --> 29:00.042
It would be a shame

29:00.129 --> 29:01.914
if our Indian neighbors
became our enemies.

29:04.699 --> 29:06.570
I'll stand by ye, Uncle.

29:06.701 --> 29:08.790
I trust you'll keep
to yourself what I've told ye.

29:08.964 --> 29:11.880
♪ ♪

29:12.011 --> 29:15.275
And for those of us that have
this knowledge of the future,

29:15.405 --> 29:17.103
it must inform our decisions.

29:18.757 --> 29:20.671
Aye, Uncle Jamie.

29:20.802 --> 29:22.499
[Jamie] You have it now too.

29:22.630 --> 29:24.893
Take heed,

29:25.024 --> 29:27.243
it can be both
a blessing and a curse.

29:27.417 --> 29:30.203
♪ ♪

29:36.687 --> 29:38.472
[Claire] Huh.

29:38.602 --> 29:40.082
Well, they've put that up fast.

29:40.213 --> 29:43.216
[solemn music plays]

29:43.303 --> 29:45.827
[Roger] Today we give thanks
for the life of this woman.

29:45.958 --> 29:48.090
A servant of God,
faithful and true.

29:49.831 --> 29:51.528
A fellow Scot
that came to this colony

29:51.659 --> 29:55.141
but now stands before
the Lord in Heaven.

29:55.271 --> 29:57.143
Is she going to eat it?

29:58.753 --> 30:00.973
No, lad.

30:01.103 --> 30:02.496
She's dead.

30:02.626 --> 30:03.889
That's for the Sin-Eater.

30:04.019 --> 30:04.933
"Sin-Eater"?

30:07.718 --> 30:09.372
God rest ye.

30:14.769 --> 30:15.726
[Roger] Let us pray.

30:17.511 --> 30:19.861
O, God, our Heavenly Father,

30:19.992 --> 30:21.907
who art leading us
through the changes of time

30:22.037 --> 30:24.823
to the rest
and blessedness of eternity,

30:24.953 --> 30:27.260
be thou near to us now,
to comfort...

30:27.390 --> 30:28.565
-Grannie.
-[Roger] ...and to uphold,

30:28.696 --> 30:30.350
-make us know...
-Shh.

30:30.437 --> 30:31.481
[Roger] ...and feel that
Thy children are precious

30:31.612 --> 30:33.266
in Thy sight,

30:33.353 --> 30:35.311
and that they live evermore
with Thee...

30:35.442 --> 30:37.009
[Germaine] Grannie.

30:37.139 --> 30:38.401
Do you need to go to the privy?

30:38.532 --> 30:40.621
No. Look.

30:40.751 --> 30:42.318
-[eerie music plays]
-[Mrs. Wilson gasps]

30:42.449 --> 30:45.104
Oh, my Lord.

30:45.191 --> 30:48.150
Roger, here.
Help me get her comfortable.

30:48.281 --> 30:49.412
[parishioners murmuring]

30:49.543 --> 30:50.936
Christ, defend us.

30:51.023 --> 30:52.851
[parishioners murmuring]

30:52.938 --> 30:55.114
[Claire] Stay back.
She needs some air.

30:55.244 --> 30:56.855
[parishioner] Is she possessed?

30:56.985 --> 30:58.073
[Claire] Mrs. Wilson?

30:58.204 --> 30:59.031
[parishioners murmuring]

30:59.118 --> 31:00.684
Can you hear me?

31:00.815 --> 31:02.556
Where...

31:02.686 --> 31:05.211
wh--where am I?

31:05.341 --> 31:07.213
You're in the church.

31:07.300 --> 31:09.302
And your family
is here with you.

31:09.389 --> 31:11.521
[Mrs. Crombie] Aye, mother.
I'm here.

31:11.652 --> 31:12.827
I'm here.

31:12.958 --> 31:14.307
What devilry is this?

31:14.394 --> 31:15.482
[Claire] Pulse is weak.

31:24.491 --> 31:26.275
It's an aortic aneurysm.

31:26.406 --> 31:27.711
She's bleeding internally.

31:27.842 --> 31:29.539
It's probably a slow leak.

31:29.626 --> 31:30.976
Long enough for her
to lose consciousness

31:31.106 --> 31:32.064
and feel cold to the touch.

31:32.194 --> 31:33.326
She will live?

31:34.327 --> 31:36.068
Not for long.

31:36.198 --> 31:38.592
Her aneurysm will rupture soon,

31:38.722 --> 31:39.810
and then she really will--

31:41.377 --> 31:43.423
She has minutes, at most.

31:43.553 --> 31:46.078
[Mrs. Wilson breathing shakily]

31:48.689 --> 31:51.474
What sort of a funeral
is this?

31:51.605 --> 31:55.174
Why, Hiram Crombie,
ye shameless skinflint.

31:57.132 --> 31:59.569
Have ye laid me out in a barn

31:59.700 --> 32:00.875
with nothing
but a crust of bread

32:01.006 --> 32:02.877
and a drop o' wine
for the Sin-Eater?

32:02.964 --> 32:04.748
"Skinflint"?

32:04.835 --> 32:07.273
And where is my good brooch

32:07.403 --> 32:09.797
I said I wanted
to be buried with?

32:09.884 --> 32:11.494
Stole it for yer own,
nae doubt.

32:11.625 --> 32:13.322
[Hiram] Stole it?

32:13.453 --> 32:15.498
Have I not given you a home
these past 20 years?

32:15.629 --> 32:17.457
Fed and clothed you
as my own mother,

32:17.587 --> 32:18.893
put up with your
wicked tongue?

32:19.024 --> 32:20.199
My tongue, wicked?

32:20.286 --> 32:21.765
Good people, enough.

32:21.896 --> 32:23.028
I'll not have this.

32:23.158 --> 32:25.204
It's not fitting,
and I won't have it.

32:25.334 --> 32:28.163
[lively string music plays]

32:28.250 --> 32:32.080
Mrs. Wilson, do you not know
that you stand before God?

32:32.211 --> 32:34.735
As do you.

32:34.865 --> 32:38.086
I--I'm afraid you're closer.

32:38.217 --> 32:40.915
Your condition's temporary.

32:41.046 --> 32:42.961
You are still bound
for eternity.

32:43.048 --> 32:45.137
It's best you try
to compose your soul.

32:45.267 --> 32:47.966
[footsteps approaching]

32:49.445 --> 32:50.490
[parishioner] The Sin-Eater.

32:50.664 --> 32:53.406
♪ ♪

32:59.107 --> 33:01.805
You're not dead.

33:01.936 --> 33:04.591
What of it?

33:04.721 --> 33:07.594
Did not my son-in-law
pay ye to eat my sins?

33:09.639 --> 33:11.728
Ye did pay him, Hiram.

33:11.859 --> 33:14.601
Well, I'm not gonna pay him
before he's done a job.

33:14.731 --> 33:16.864
What sort of a way
is that to be carrying on?

33:16.951 --> 33:19.388
I--I brought the money.

33:19.519 --> 33:20.650
I have it.

33:23.479 --> 33:26.134
Well...

33:26.265 --> 33:28.136
ye best be about
your business, sir.

33:31.879 --> 33:34.664
[soft string music plays]

33:34.838 --> 33:37.580
♪ ♪

33:42.368 --> 33:45.719
I give easement
and rest to thee,

33:45.806 --> 33:49.853
and for thy peace,
in Christ's name,

33:49.940 --> 33:52.030
I pawn my own soul.

34:01.343 --> 34:04.390
♪ ♪

34:04.520 --> 34:07.306
[Mrs. Wilson breathing shakily]

34:16.837 --> 34:19.100
I forgive ye, Hiram.

34:21.233 --> 34:22.973
Ye've been a good lad.

34:26.368 --> 34:27.543
Ah.

34:29.241 --> 34:31.591
I am not afraid.

34:31.765 --> 34:34.159
♪ ♪

34:35.899 --> 34:38.119
[exhales breathily]

34:39.642 --> 34:41.383
[both sob]

34:41.470 --> 34:44.256
♪ ♪

34:45.866 --> 34:48.651
[muffled sobs]

35:10.238 --> 35:13.067
"I am the resurrection
and the Life, saith the Lord.

35:15.678 --> 35:17.898
"He that believeth in me
though he were dead,

35:18.028 --> 35:20.814
"yet shall he live.

35:20.944 --> 35:24.426
"And whosoever liveth
and believeth in me

35:24.557 --> 35:26.167
shall never die."

35:26.254 --> 35:29.127
[emotional music plays]

35:29.214 --> 35:31.825
♪ ♪

35:31.955 --> 35:34.132
[whispering] And sometimes,
out of the flames--

35:34.262 --> 35:36.308
out of the flames
comes a parrot,

35:36.438 --> 35:39.441
a parrot with a big sort of...

35:39.572 --> 35:42.401
Thank you, Mrs. Bug.
This looks delicious.

35:42.531 --> 35:44.359
'Tis a new recipe
I'm trying for the neeps.

35:44.490 --> 35:46.274
[Marsali chuckles]

35:46.361 --> 35:48.146
I'm not sure there's room
in my belly for anything else.

35:48.276 --> 35:50.235
Will Mr. Fraser be joining us?

35:50.365 --> 35:52.062
No.

35:52.150 --> 35:54.021
Er, he's at the still.

35:54.152 --> 35:56.719
Of course he is.
Forgive me, my dear.

36:00.549 --> 36:02.943
[Brianna] Uh, we have
some exciting news.

36:05.075 --> 36:06.425
Well, more Brianna than me.

36:06.512 --> 36:08.644
You're with child.

36:08.731 --> 36:11.299
Oh! I dinna envy ye, Bree,
but I'm very happy for ye both.

36:11.430 --> 36:13.693
A--a toast!
And get the whisky, Sassenach.

36:13.823 --> 36:15.651
No, no. Stop, no.

36:15.782 --> 36:17.523
I'm not with child.

36:20.700 --> 36:23.355
I was going to say
that I have a surprise.

36:26.445 --> 36:27.359
I've invented something.

36:32.712 --> 36:33.626
-[Jamie chuckles]
-[Claire] Ah.

36:35.454 --> 36:36.846
[Marsali] Wee...

36:36.977 --> 36:39.675
wee bit of flint, is it?

36:39.806 --> 36:41.416
Well, no,
it's easier than flint.

36:41.547 --> 36:42.939
They're called matches.

36:43.070 --> 36:44.419
They're easier to light,
it's faster,

36:44.506 --> 36:45.420
and they hold a flame.

36:45.551 --> 36:46.639
You can take them with you

36:46.769 --> 36:48.162
and light a fire
wherever you go.

36:48.293 --> 36:50.382
Oh, never had trouble
lighting a fire.

36:50.512 --> 36:51.513
Putting one out, maybe.

36:51.644 --> 36:52.906
[both chuckle]

36:56.562 --> 36:58.607
Well, I'm sorry it's not
the news you expected.

36:58.694 --> 37:01.741
Not so. Well done, a leannan.

37:01.828 --> 37:05.440
These uh, matches
will be very useful.

37:05.571 --> 37:07.355
I think it's wonderful,
darling,

37:07.486 --> 37:08.617
and I, for one,
can't wait to use them.

37:10.184 --> 37:11.446
Thank you.

37:11.577 --> 37:13.709
Well done, you too, Roger,

37:13.840 --> 37:15.276
for your deft handling

37:15.407 --> 37:16.973
of Grannie Wilson's
strange funeral.

37:17.104 --> 37:18.410
Aye.

37:18.497 --> 37:20.238
So rousin'
I hear ye woke the dead.

37:21.500 --> 37:23.589
Well, Mr. Christie must have
been impressed, anyway.

37:23.719 --> 37:26.766
He's asked if I might
preach the sermon on Sunday.

37:26.896 --> 37:28.376
As a lay minister, of course.

37:28.507 --> 37:29.899
He did?

37:30.030 --> 37:31.336
Why doesn't Tom do it?

37:31.466 --> 37:33.251
Well, Tom's not a preacher.

37:33.381 --> 37:35.078
Neither are you.

37:35.165 --> 37:37.080
It's just temporary.

37:37.211 --> 37:39.605
Maybe the reverend's up there
watching me, proud.

37:39.735 --> 37:41.215
There's any preaching
to be done,

37:41.346 --> 37:43.565
I'd rather you do it
than Tom Christie.

37:43.696 --> 37:47.003
I've known him to stir up
trouble with his beliefs.

37:47.090 --> 37:48.483
I'll not have it on the Ridge.

37:48.614 --> 37:50.180
I'm happy to fill in.

37:51.443 --> 37:53.575
I was asked to never darken
the doors of the church again.

37:53.706 --> 37:55.621
What?

37:55.751 --> 37:57.449
Apparently,

37:57.579 --> 38:00.321
due to Mrs. Wilson's
rising from the dead,

38:00.452 --> 38:03.324
some of the new settlers
think that I am a witch.

38:03.455 --> 38:05.805
-[Claire chuckles]
-And that doesn't bother you?

38:05.892 --> 38:08.024
Well, it's not as if it's
the first time I've heard it.

38:08.155 --> 38:09.374
And besides, I've no intention

38:09.504 --> 38:11.027
of complying
with their demands.

38:12.333 --> 38:13.465
[Roger] Especially since I'll
be doing the preaching now.

38:13.595 --> 38:14.814
-[Claire] Hmm.
-Wouldn't want to miss that.

38:14.944 --> 38:15.728
[Claire laughs] No.

38:15.815 --> 38:17.033
[all chuckle]

38:18.252 --> 38:20.123
Oh!

38:20.254 --> 38:21.864
Ah! Ah!

38:21.995 --> 38:23.083
Marsali?

38:23.213 --> 38:25.564
[Marsali] Lord Almighty!

38:25.651 --> 38:27.130
Something feels wrong.

38:27.261 --> 38:28.567
Claire, something feels
different from before.

38:28.697 --> 38:30.264
Here, help me get her
to the surgery.

38:30.395 --> 38:31.831
-Ah.
-Okay.

38:40.143 --> 38:41.057
[Marsali shudders]

38:41.188 --> 38:43.146
[Jamie] Seaweed?

38:43.277 --> 38:44.713
Laminaria.

38:44.844 --> 38:46.454
You place it into the cervix,

38:46.541 --> 38:49.109
and it absorbs the moisture
and forces it to open further.

38:49.239 --> 38:50.719
To help the bairn along?

38:52.678 --> 38:55.245
I thought perhaps
it was already on its way.

38:55.376 --> 38:58.205
We had one contraction earlier.

38:58.336 --> 39:00.338
The baby hasn't moved in hours.

39:00.468 --> 39:03.079
[somber string music plays]

39:03.166 --> 39:06.213
♪ ♪

39:06.300 --> 39:07.432
What is it, Sassenach?

39:07.519 --> 39:10.565
[Marsali moaning]

39:10.696 --> 39:13.133
[Claire] Could be anything.

39:13.263 --> 39:15.527
Things I'm completely
unprepared to deal with here.

39:17.703 --> 39:19.879
Now, I could perform
a Caesarian

39:20.009 --> 39:21.750
to save the baby, but--

39:23.230 --> 39:24.362
But not Marsali.

39:30.542 --> 39:32.282
Where the hell is Fergus?

39:32.674 --> 39:34.067
I was hoping you would know.

39:35.677 --> 39:37.157
Marsali said
that he's feeling guilty

39:37.287 --> 39:39.289
about what happened with us,
with the--

39:39.420 --> 39:40.943
with the Browns.

39:41.074 --> 39:42.031
Well, aye, he would.

39:43.990 --> 39:46.079
Why?

39:46.166 --> 39:47.863
It's not his fault.

39:48.255 --> 39:49.474
It makes no difference.

39:52.041 --> 39:55.218
If Marsali should die
or mischief come to the child,

39:55.349 --> 39:56.045
do ye think
he'd not blame himself?

39:57.960 --> 39:59.701
Ye think I dinna curse myself
every day

39:59.832 --> 40:01.790
for what happened to you?

40:01.921 --> 40:04.793
There's nothing either of you
could have done to prevent it.

40:04.924 --> 40:06.708
Besides,
you came to our rescue.

40:08.231 --> 40:10.277
You better find him quickly,

40:10.364 --> 40:12.366
or he may end up
regretting this too.

40:14.542 --> 40:15.978
I'll have Roger fetch him.

40:16.109 --> 40:17.937
[Marsali moans]

40:20.069 --> 40:22.332
-Bree.
-I brought Malva.

40:22.463 --> 40:24.204
Malva, thank you for coming.

40:24.334 --> 40:26.815
If you're truly interested
in helping me,

40:26.946 --> 40:28.774
then tonight's the night.

40:28.861 --> 40:30.384
I'm pleased to be here,
Mistress.

40:30.515 --> 40:32.342
[Marsali moans]

40:32.430 --> 40:35.258
[dramatic music plays]

40:35.345 --> 40:38.131
♪ ♪

40:52.188 --> 40:54.452
What in God's name
are you playing at?

40:54.582 --> 40:57.063
Your wife's at the big house
having your child.

40:57.193 --> 40:58.847
Claire's with her.

40:58.978 --> 41:01.023
She can take care of her.

41:01.154 --> 41:03.243
I'd be in the way.

41:03.373 --> 41:04.723
She wants you.

41:07.073 --> 41:08.248
She needs you.

41:11.077 --> 41:13.296
What can I do?

41:13.383 --> 41:14.863
I don't know what it is
you can do,

41:14.994 --> 41:16.212
but she thinks
there's something.

41:18.127 --> 41:19.433
She's been crying out for you.

41:21.609 --> 41:23.045
Fergus.

41:25.004 --> 41:28.007
You'll regret it
if you're not there, trust me.

41:28.137 --> 41:29.835
Maybe not today,
but there'll come a time

41:29.965 --> 41:31.227
where you'll look at
your child and you'll-

41:32.968 --> 41:34.361
You'll never forgive yourself

41:34.448 --> 41:36.319
if you're not with Marsali
on this blessed day.

41:36.450 --> 41:38.278
No. No.

41:41.760 --> 41:43.370
Leave me alone, yeah?
It's too late.

41:43.501 --> 41:46.329
Bloody hell, Fergus.
Your wife is in harm's way.

41:46.460 --> 41:48.462
I don't know what it is
that has you in this state,

41:48.593 --> 41:50.072
but it doesn't matter.

41:50.203 --> 41:52.161
Marsali needs you now.

41:54.773 --> 41:56.775
So for tonight,
pull yourself together

41:56.905 --> 41:58.733
and be the man
that Marsali thinks you are--

41:58.864 --> 42:00.387
the man that you
promised her you'd be.

42:02.084 --> 42:03.259
Even if you have to pretend.

42:05.697 --> 42:08.047
And maybe when you see her,
you won't have to.

42:19.667 --> 42:21.582
Just give some time for
the laminaria to do its work.

42:30.330 --> 42:31.940
Thank you, Malva.

42:32.071 --> 42:33.246
I'll make some tea.

42:41.167 --> 42:43.691
Adso...

42:43.822 --> 42:46.607
if I am to die...

42:46.738 --> 42:48.174
don't be letting
Mistress Fraser

42:48.304 --> 42:49.610
be doing any autopsies on me.

42:53.092 --> 42:54.310
[exhales sharply]

43:00.490 --> 43:01.883
I dinna doubt yer skill,
Claire.

43:04.407 --> 43:05.539
But I ken ye well enough.

43:08.281 --> 43:09.848
I ken what ye look like
when you're worried.

43:13.852 --> 43:15.418
D'ye think I could...

43:15.549 --> 43:17.290
have some paper
and some ink?

43:18.465 --> 43:19.858
Of course.

43:19.988 --> 43:20.728
Why?

43:22.817 --> 43:24.253
I think...

43:24.384 --> 43:26.212
it would be as well

43:26.342 --> 43:27.996
that I write to my mother.

43:28.127 --> 43:29.607
Marsali.

43:33.219 --> 43:36.265
-You're going to be all right.
-Mm-hmm.

43:36.396 --> 43:39.007
And I will do everything
in my power to make that so.

43:39.138 --> 43:40.443
Mm-hmm.

43:40.530 --> 43:42.576
[breathes shakily]

43:42.663 --> 43:45.971
But if it will help
put your mind at ease,

43:46.101 --> 43:48.495
-then of course.
-Mm-hmm.

43:48.626 --> 43:51.063
[footsteps approaching]

43:51.193 --> 43:53.108
[Fergus breathing heavily]

43:55.023 --> 43:57.025
[Fergus] Mon amour,
I'm here now.

43:57.156 --> 43:59.637
-How are you?
-Better now.

43:59.767 --> 44:01.464
The baby needs to come quickly.

44:01.595 --> 44:03.205
Help me, mon cher.

44:05.512 --> 44:06.513
[Fergus] I'm here for you.

44:10.517 --> 44:12.171
[moans]

44:13.694 --> 44:15.696
[sniffles]

44:15.827 --> 44:18.046
[Fergus] I'm here. I'm here.

44:21.484 --> 44:24.226
[Marsali moaning]

44:30.755 --> 44:33.105
I suppose you would not
have heard of this, milady?

44:35.063 --> 44:38.153
But when the birth pangs
are slow to start,

44:38.284 --> 44:40.373
suckling and massaging
the woman's breasts

44:40.503 --> 44:41.766
encourages the womb to move.

44:44.203 --> 44:46.118
I've heard of it before,

44:46.248 --> 44:50.078
but it's... not quite
the conventional method.

44:50.209 --> 44:54.692
In the brothel,
if les filleshad a difficulty,

44:54.822 --> 44:56.694
another would do
such service for her.

44:58.652 --> 45:00.872
I've done it before.
It helps.

45:01.002 --> 45:01.873
When Joan came.

45:04.092 --> 45:07.226
I think I'll uh, give you
both some privacy.

45:07.356 --> 45:09.968
[emotional string music plays]

45:10.142 --> 45:12.884
♪ ♪

45:20.979 --> 45:23.459
Fergus.

45:23.590 --> 45:25.374
[sniffles]

45:25.505 --> 45:26.549
I think I'm gonna die.

45:32.468 --> 45:34.906
You always think you'll die.

45:35.036 --> 45:35.950
All women think it.

45:36.037 --> 45:37.952
Aye.

45:38.083 --> 45:39.737
That's because
a great many of them do.

45:43.697 --> 45:45.133
Not you.

45:46.918 --> 45:48.310
I'll not let you go.

45:51.574 --> 45:54.316
[uplifting music plays]

45:54.403 --> 45:57.189
♪ ♪

46:14.510 --> 46:16.817
[liquid pouring]

46:16.904 --> 46:19.733
[Marsali moaning]

46:19.864 --> 46:21.866
You sure the lass is safe
in there wi' him?

46:23.955 --> 46:25.826
Quite sure.

46:25.957 --> 46:28.307
I dinna ken a man could have
so much to do at this part.

46:30.265 --> 46:31.614
Well...

46:31.745 --> 46:34.008
[moaning continues]

46:34.095 --> 46:37.229
[Jamie] Well... huh.

46:37.969 --> 46:39.753
That's what the wee bugger's
up to, then, uh...

46:39.884 --> 46:42.016
I'm gonna go for a walk.
[clears throat]

46:42.147 --> 46:43.365
There's some post
needs sorting.

46:52.461 --> 46:53.506
They're really...

46:56.901 --> 46:57.815
[Claire] Yes.

47:01.166 --> 47:02.558
At first, I thought
she was in pain.

47:04.996 --> 47:06.867
But some women...

47:06.954 --> 47:07.825
like it?

47:09.261 --> 47:10.653
They do.

47:10.740 --> 47:12.699
[soft music plays]

47:12.830 --> 47:15.049
Sinners, you mean? Whores?

47:16.703 --> 47:17.835
No.

47:19.662 --> 47:21.447
No, I mean...

47:21.577 --> 47:22.752
well...

47:24.406 --> 47:26.452
...when you love someone,

47:26.582 --> 47:28.846
well, you want
to give them pleasure.

47:30.543 --> 47:33.285
And they want to do
the same for you.

47:36.331 --> 47:38.638
You know, many women...

47:38.768 --> 47:40.379
they enjoy it.

47:48.691 --> 47:52.870
[speaking Mohawk]

47:59.964 --> 48:00.878
Sorry.

48:04.142 --> 48:06.448
Just saying a prayer
for the bairn.

48:13.847 --> 48:14.848
Cousin?

48:18.330 --> 48:20.245
Can I ask you
about the Cherokee?

48:20.375 --> 48:22.551
What about them?

48:22.682 --> 48:25.380
Uncle Jamie told me
of the Revolution.

48:25.467 --> 48:27.295
He spoke of a new country
after the war.

48:28.644 --> 48:30.516
The United States of America.

48:30.603 --> 48:31.996
United?

48:35.042 --> 48:36.435
And the Indians
will be a part of this nation?

48:46.010 --> 48:49.056
White people will tell them
that they are,

48:49.187 --> 48:51.276
but no.

48:51.406 --> 48:53.887
No, not--not really.

48:54.018 --> 48:57.021
They'll be forced to live
in places far away

48:57.151 --> 48:59.023
from their ancestral homes.

48:59.153 --> 49:00.154
But why?

49:01.721 --> 49:03.157
The Cherokee are strong.

49:03.288 --> 49:04.419
Not strong enough.

49:07.727 --> 49:11.905
Settlers have been coming
and will continue to come,

49:12.036 --> 49:13.733
from all over the world.

49:13.820 --> 49:17.780
They'll take what they want,
and...

49:17.911 --> 49:19.695
the Indians will suffer
because of it.

49:22.829 --> 49:24.439
I'm sorry.

49:24.787 --> 49:26.354
Why are you apologizing?

49:27.747 --> 49:29.488
Because...

49:29.618 --> 49:31.359
knowing what happens to them...

49:34.275 --> 49:36.669
...I'm responsible too.

49:36.799 --> 49:39.193
[somber music plays]

49:39.324 --> 49:40.325
The bairn's coming.

49:40.499 --> 49:43.197
♪ ♪

49:48.550 --> 49:51.075
[Claire] Okay. Now push.

49:51.205 --> 49:52.511
[Marsali groans]

49:52.598 --> 49:56.123
That's it. Not too hard.

49:56.254 --> 49:57.733
The head's rather large.

49:57.864 --> 50:00.040
Is that so?

50:00.171 --> 50:01.955
All right, and breathe.

50:02.086 --> 50:03.870
[both breathing heavily]

50:05.002 --> 50:07.352
[Claire] That's it.
You ready to go again?

50:07.482 --> 50:10.007
One, two, three,

50:10.137 --> 50:11.747
and push!

50:11.878 --> 50:14.533
[Marsali groans]

50:16.317 --> 50:18.363
Well?

50:18.450 --> 50:20.060
Listen for yourself.

50:20.191 --> 50:22.193
[Claire] One last time.

50:22.323 --> 50:25.587
One, two, three.

50:25.718 --> 50:28.242
-Push!
-[Marsali groaning]

50:32.551 --> 50:35.293
[baby crying]

50:44.519 --> 50:45.868
Papa.

50:58.620 --> 50:59.665
-Never again.
-No.

50:59.795 --> 51:01.275
Fergus Fraser.

51:01.362 --> 51:03.669
[emotional music plays]

51:05.149 --> 51:06.628
[Claire] Bonsoir,Monsieur.

51:06.759 --> 51:08.587
-Monsieur?
-Monsieur.

51:10.676 --> 51:12.460
[baby cries]

51:14.636 --> 51:17.291
[Fergus speaking French]

51:19.815 --> 51:20.816
[baby crying]

51:20.947 --> 51:22.166
Bonjour.

51:24.690 --> 51:26.083
Bonjour.

51:26.257 --> 51:29.086
♪ ♪

51:34.482 --> 51:35.831
Bonjour.

51:44.013 --> 51:45.276
[baby fusses]

51:54.459 --> 51:56.896
[tense music plays]

51:57.070 --> 51:58.115
♪ ♪

51:58.245 --> 51:59.420
Il est un nain.

52:03.859 --> 52:05.296
Fergus.

52:05.383 --> 52:06.471
[baby fusses]

52:08.037 --> 52:10.214
Fergus. Fergus.

52:10.344 --> 52:11.258
What did he say?

52:13.826 --> 52:14.740
"Nain"?What does that mean?

52:17.308 --> 52:20.137
[somber music plays]

52:20.224 --> 52:23.009
♪ ♪

52:25.098 --> 52:26.621
It means he's a dwarf.

52:29.972 --> 52:31.844
But he's perfectly healthy.

52:32.018 --> 52:34.803
♪ ♪

52:36.240 --> 52:37.806
[baby fussing]

52:46.380 --> 52:48.034
Oh.

52:52.473 --> 52:53.866
[laughs]

52:56.347 --> 52:57.957
Oh, he's beautiful.

52:58.131 --> 53:00.873
♪ ♪

53:03.658 --> 53:05.182
[baby fusses]

53:20.893 --> 53:23.678
[soft music plays]

53:23.852 --> 53:26.638
♪ ♪

53:37.736 --> 53:40.739
[chuckles]
Works like a charm.

53:40.869 --> 53:43.698
Pointless. Nobody cares.

53:43.829 --> 53:45.613
Oh, come now.

53:46.135 --> 53:47.311
What if Edison has said that?

53:48.877 --> 53:51.532
Edison was a man.

53:51.619 --> 53:55.841
Apparently the only worthwhile
thing I can do is get pregnant.

53:58.844 --> 54:01.368
Is that really
what's bothering ye?

54:01.499 --> 54:03.065
Or is it that we've been trying
for a while now?

54:05.154 --> 54:06.243
Maybe it's just not
the right time.

54:08.636 --> 54:11.422
And seeing as we have decided
to stay here for good,

54:11.552 --> 54:13.641
I guess I should be patient.

54:21.780 --> 54:22.824
[knocks on door]

54:35.881 --> 54:36.838
[Roger] Aidan.

54:39.363 --> 54:41.539
What are you doing here?
Come in, lad.

54:41.669 --> 54:42.627
[Brianna] Are you all right?

54:44.455 --> 54:45.673
You must be cold.

54:45.804 --> 54:47.414
Come on.
Let's get you by the fire.

54:49.547 --> 54:51.026
[Roger] Is everything
all right?

54:51.157 --> 54:52.550
I was out chasing rabbits.

54:52.680 --> 54:54.247
I tried to make my way home,

54:54.378 --> 54:56.510
but must've got
turned about in the dark.

54:56.641 --> 54:58.469
Well, I was just going
for a walk.

54:58.599 --> 55:00.688
Why don't I show you the way?

55:01.298 --> 55:02.647
Your mother must be worried
about you.

55:02.777 --> 55:03.996
Get you home.

55:04.649 --> 55:06.215
Aidan, would you like
to see a marvel?

55:07.478 --> 55:08.870
A trick of sorts?

55:09.001 --> 55:09.741
Aye.

55:11.308 --> 55:13.222
Watch the stick very closely.

55:17.575 --> 55:20.055
How did you do that?
It's a miracle.

55:20.186 --> 55:21.970
[chuckles]
It's not a miracle, lad.

55:22.101 --> 55:23.755
It's science.

55:23.885 --> 55:25.539
My wife made it.

55:25.626 --> 55:27.454
She's a genius.

55:27.585 --> 55:30.283
[sentimental music plays]

55:30.457 --> 55:33.242
♪ ♪

55:45.820 --> 55:49.215
The fox pelts should fetch
a good sum at Cross Creek.

55:49.346 --> 55:52.087
Well, when ye take the whisky
onward to River Run,

55:52.218 --> 55:54.133
be grateful if you'd see if my
aunt has any letters for me.

55:54.263 --> 55:55.656
Yer humble servant, sir.

55:58.703 --> 56:01.009
Bread and sausage
for the week, as requested.

56:02.402 --> 56:05.536
Don't envy yer gut, Mr. Bug,

56:05.666 --> 56:07.102
nor that one's nose.

56:08.669 --> 56:10.105
We'd best be on our way, lad.

56:13.935 --> 56:16.111
Be safe, Kezzie. Hurry back.

56:16.242 --> 56:18.897
You mean you'll miss me,
Lizzie?

56:19.027 --> 56:20.594
A wee bit, perhaps.

56:20.681 --> 56:22.857
But dinna let that
go your head.

56:22.988 --> 56:24.685
I'll try and keep your brother
out of trouble.

56:26.818 --> 56:28.428
I hope you're not
the talkative one.

56:59.981 --> 57:01.896
Chief Bird.

57:02.027 --> 57:02.984
You're most welcome.

57:04.421 --> 57:05.987
I'm glad of it.

57:07.249 --> 57:09.251
Seeing as we gave you
a warm welcome in our village.

57:11.166 --> 57:12.298
Is there something
we can do for you?

57:14.169 --> 57:16.433
Did you convey my request
for guns to your king?

57:18.304 --> 57:20.480
I decided against it.

57:21.176 --> 57:22.874
Why did you not convey
my request?

57:24.963 --> 57:26.704
You must trust me.

57:26.791 --> 57:28.401
It's for the best.

57:28.532 --> 57:31.230
[tense music plays]

57:31.404 --> 57:34.712
♪ ♪

57:34.842 --> 57:36.583
This is not the last
you'll see of us, Bear-Killer.

57:50.205 --> 57:51.380
Speak, lad.

57:52.947 --> 57:54.209
Can tell you want to.

57:55.776 --> 57:57.822
I canna agree
with yer decision.

57:59.432 --> 58:01.260
Despite what I told you before?

58:01.390 --> 58:04.437
Because of what
you told me before.

58:04.524 --> 58:05.960
I have a kinship with them.

58:06.091 --> 58:08.006
And what of our kinship?

58:08.136 --> 58:10.095
You ken well my reasons.

58:10.878 --> 58:12.837
You told me that my knowledge
of what's to come

58:12.967 --> 58:14.752
must inform my choices.

58:14.882 --> 58:15.970
Aye. So?

58:16.101 --> 58:18.495
Then that's my reasoning.

58:18.625 --> 58:20.148
Brianna told me
of the injustices

58:20.279 --> 58:22.107
the Indians will face.

58:22.237 --> 58:24.849
If that is their fate,
then they deserve

58:24.979 --> 58:27.460
every chance
to protect themselves.

58:27.591 --> 58:29.984
And if you willna help them,
then I will.

58:30.115 --> 58:32.073
And where do you expect
to find guns for them?

58:32.204 --> 58:33.422
How will you pay for them?

58:33.553 --> 58:35.163
Dinna ken.

58:35.294 --> 58:36.382
But I'll find a way.

58:43.998 --> 58:46.479
[rain pouring]

59:02.669 --> 59:05.063
[Brianna] Should we
start calling you Atlas?

59:06.673 --> 59:08.066
You look like you've got

59:08.196 --> 59:09.371
the weight of the world
on your shoulders.

59:09.502 --> 59:10.895
[Jamie] Hm.

59:11.939 --> 59:14.376
Heaven and Earth
and everything in between.

59:17.379 --> 59:19.338
[Brianna] Well, whatever it is,

59:19.425 --> 59:20.774
I hope it's nothing
too serious.

59:22.776 --> 59:25.170
I'm not sure there's much
ever put right in this world

59:25.300 --> 59:27.999
with gunpowder and bullets.

59:28.129 --> 59:30.175
It seems one of the ways
most favored by men.

59:32.612 --> 59:34.440
You, um...

59:34.571 --> 59:36.964
you were up at the fisherfolk
camp this morning.

59:37.095 --> 59:40.098
Yes. I was with Roger
at Amy MacCallum's.

59:40.228 --> 59:41.012
Building her a cabin.

59:42.013 --> 59:43.492
Aye, I heard.

59:44.581 --> 59:46.670
They're really making
good progress over there.

59:46.800 --> 59:48.062
Tom's nearly finished
with the church.

59:48.193 --> 59:49.281
They're working
on a steeple now.

59:57.985 --> 59:59.334
You don't seem too pleased.

59:59.465 --> 1:00:00.640
[sighs]

1:00:02.860 --> 1:00:05.863
The church
in Tom Christie's hands...

1:00:05.993 --> 1:00:07.821
can become a weapon of war.

1:00:07.952 --> 1:00:10.737
[emotional music plays]

1:00:10.911 --> 1:00:13.610
♪ ♪

1:00:23.532 --> 1:00:25.709
[hammering]

1:00:25.839 --> 1:00:28.625
[sawing]

1:00:38.156 --> 1:00:40.114
[horse whinnies]

1:00:40.245 --> 1:00:42.160
[indistinct chatter]

1:00:42.290 --> 1:00:43.074
Mr. Christie.

1:00:45.946 --> 1:00:46.686
[Tom] Aye.

1:00:49.297 --> 1:00:51.256
What do you think?

1:00:51.386 --> 1:00:52.170
[Jamie] Thought ye
were intending

1:00:52.300 --> 1:00:53.258
on building a cabin here.

1:00:54.999 --> 1:00:56.827
I didna say anything before,

1:00:56.957 --> 1:00:58.742
out of respect
for Mistress Wilson, but--

1:00:58.829 --> 1:01:00.091
As I told your son-in-law,

1:01:00.221 --> 1:01:01.832
a man must build
a house for God

1:01:01.962 --> 1:01:03.268
before he builds one
for himself.

1:01:07.011 --> 1:01:09.361
We've come a long way
since Ardsmuir, Tom.

1:01:09.448 --> 1:01:11.755
Aye.

1:01:11.842 --> 1:01:13.974
That place was enough
to make any man lose faith,

1:01:14.105 --> 1:01:17.064
but... I'm glad to see
you've kept God first.

1:01:17.195 --> 1:01:18.936
But...

1:01:19.066 --> 1:01:21.503
well...

1:01:21.634 --> 1:01:24.071
you willna have forgotten
your Freemason's vow, will ye?

1:01:25.551 --> 1:01:27.596
Uh...

1:01:27.727 --> 1:01:28.772
no.

1:01:28.902 --> 1:01:29.773
No.

1:01:31.426 --> 1:01:32.906
Then let this
be a meeting house.

1:01:35.300 --> 1:01:37.911
Neither Protestant
nor Catholic.

1:01:39.304 --> 1:01:42.263
A place where every man, woman,
and child may enter freely,

1:01:42.394 --> 1:01:43.787
with God in their hearts.

1:01:45.266 --> 1:01:46.920
Every man, woman, and child.

1:01:47.007 --> 1:01:48.661
Aye.

1:01:48.792 --> 1:01:50.445
[tense music plays]

1:01:50.532 --> 1:01:52.186
My wife too, Tom.

1:01:52.273 --> 1:01:55.059
♪ ♪

1:01:57.626 --> 1:01:59.063
And if I hear of anyone
accusing her

1:01:59.150 --> 1:02:00.717
of witchcraft again...

1:02:05.417 --> 1:02:07.506
I suppose you'll have me
bring down the steeple, then.

1:02:15.253 --> 1:02:16.210
No.

1:02:17.734 --> 1:02:19.953
It's a bonnie sight.

1:02:20.084 --> 1:02:21.215
It should have a bell.

1:02:22.869 --> 1:02:26.046
One that calls all to worship,

1:02:26.177 --> 1:02:27.395
or to their lessons.

1:02:29.049 --> 1:02:32.096
As I said... a meeting place.

1:02:41.105 --> 1:02:43.934
Some windowpanes
wouldna go amiss either.

1:02:45.152 --> 1:02:48.547
Always good to have windowpanes
on a meeting house.

1:02:58.600 --> 1:03:01.342
[tense music plays]

1:03:01.516 --> 1:03:04.302
♪ ♪

1:03:28.848 --> 1:03:31.285
♪ ♪

1:03:31.416 --> 1:03:32.634
The milk has turned.

1:03:33.766 --> 1:03:34.985
Sorry.

1:03:35.115 --> 1:03:35.812
I was going
to make some butter.

1:03:35.899 --> 1:03:37.726
Why haven't ye?

1:03:37.814 --> 1:03:40.033
It must have slipped my mind.

1:03:40.164 --> 1:03:41.643
Mistress MacNeill
brought us some ale, father.

1:03:41.730 --> 1:03:42.514
would you like some?

1:03:42.644 --> 1:03:44.777
I don't want ale.

1:03:44.908 --> 1:03:46.518
I want milk.

1:03:47.562 --> 1:03:49.390
"Come to a land
of milk and honey," eh?

1:03:51.523 --> 1:03:52.872
What do I have?

1:03:52.959 --> 1:03:54.308
Nothing!

1:03:54.482 --> 1:03:57.311
♪ ♪

1:03:57.398 --> 1:03:58.965
It's because
you're spending too much time

1:03:59.096 --> 1:04:00.314
with Mistress Fraser!

1:04:02.273 --> 1:04:04.188
You have the same...

1:04:04.318 --> 1:04:05.711
dark soul as your mother!

1:04:07.887 --> 1:04:09.236
And you know
what became of her.

1:04:14.154 --> 1:04:14.938
Stand up!

1:04:20.639 --> 1:04:22.815
I won't ask you again, Malva.

1:04:22.946 --> 1:04:25.687
[chilling music plays]

1:04:25.862 --> 1:04:28.821
♪ ♪

1:04:29.126 --> 1:04:30.214
I didn't do anything.

1:04:31.389 --> 1:04:33.086
Lift your skirts.

1:04:33.260 --> 1:04:36.002
♪ ♪

1:04:47.492 --> 1:04:48.754
Damn hand!

1:04:49.798 --> 1:04:50.799
Damn hand!

1:04:50.930 --> 1:04:52.279
[grunts]

1:05:08.121 --> 1:05:10.863
[Tom pants]

1:05:23.745 --> 1:05:25.356
Take that look off your face.

1:05:38.282 --> 1:05:41.067
♪ ♪

1:05:43.156 --> 1:05:45.506
His name is Henri-Christian.

1:05:50.772 --> 1:05:53.601
[speaking Mohawk]

1:06:09.400 --> 1:06:11.141
[Marsali] What was that
you said?

1:06:11.271 --> 1:06:14.405
A sort of blessin'.

1:06:14.535 --> 1:06:17.669
You call upon the wind
to welcome him,

1:06:17.799 --> 1:06:20.324
the sky to give him shelter,

1:06:20.454 --> 1:06:22.195
and the water and the earth
to yield him food.

1:06:36.601 --> 1:06:38.298
I had a child.

1:06:38.429 --> 1:06:41.214
[somber music plays]

1:06:41.301 --> 1:06:44.043
♪ ♪

1:06:49.309 --> 1:06:50.484
Did ye?

1:06:54.314 --> 1:06:56.490
Believe me, cousin,

1:06:56.621 --> 1:06:58.579
your husband grieves,

1:06:58.710 --> 1:07:00.059
but he'll come back.

1:07:09.634 --> 1:07:11.897
Mr. Christie.

1:07:12.028 --> 1:07:14.117
-What brings you here?
-[Tom] Uh...

1:07:14.247 --> 1:07:17.424
My hand is worse. It's, uh--

1:07:17.555 --> 1:07:20.645
it's preventing me
from... writing.

1:07:20.732 --> 1:07:23.561
And-and I have considered
the matter

1:07:23.691 --> 1:07:25.650
and prayed upon it,

1:07:25.737 --> 1:07:28.696
and I understand now

1:07:28.827 --> 1:07:31.786
that God brought you to me
for a reason.

1:07:35.051 --> 1:07:38.793
I will undergo
your... operation.

1:07:38.880 --> 1:07:40.665
Well, who am I to stand
in the way

1:07:40.752 --> 1:07:41.796
of the Almighty's plans?

1:07:42.928 --> 1:07:44.538
But as I told you before,

1:07:44.669 --> 1:07:46.627
we need to let that left hand
heal properly first.

1:07:50.283 --> 1:07:52.546
-[Tom] Aye.
-So come back then.

1:08:38.940 --> 1:08:40.203
Who are you writing to?

1:08:42.379 --> 1:08:43.423
The governor.

1:08:45.033 --> 1:08:46.861
So, you've decided to pass along

1:08:46.992 --> 1:08:48.211
Chief Bird's request
for weapons?

1:08:49.647 --> 1:08:51.779
More than that.

1:08:51.910 --> 1:08:53.781
I'm recommending
we do as they ask.

1:08:53.868 --> 1:08:55.218
Come what may?

1:08:55.348 --> 1:08:56.567
[Jamie] Hm.

1:08:56.654 --> 1:08:59.700
I may have cause
to regret it, but...

1:08:59.787 --> 1:09:01.702
if Governor Martin
sees fit,

1:09:01.833 --> 1:09:04.314
the Cherokee will have
their guns,

1:09:04.444 --> 1:09:05.619
to do with them as they please.

1:09:08.013 --> 1:09:10.450
I, uh...

1:09:10.581 --> 1:09:13.105
I'll give the letter
to Major MacDonald

1:09:13.236 --> 1:09:14.454
before he leaves.

1:09:18.328 --> 1:09:19.981
What made you change your mind?

1:09:24.682 --> 1:09:25.857
Ian.

1:09:27.119 --> 1:09:29.426
He, uh...

1:09:29.556 --> 1:09:33.430
he had a child
with his Mohawk wife.

1:09:33.560 --> 1:09:35.432
He what?

1:09:35.562 --> 1:09:37.477
He told Marsali.

1:09:37.608 --> 1:09:38.870
Dinna say more about it.

1:09:43.396 --> 1:09:45.137
He fights for them because...

1:09:45.268 --> 1:09:48.096
they are his family.

1:09:48.227 --> 1:09:50.534
His allegiance is to them.

1:09:53.493 --> 1:09:55.321
And my allegiance is to him.

1:09:57.715 --> 1:09:59.456
Well, I think
it's the right thing to do.

1:10:01.284 --> 1:10:04.112
[solemn music plays]

1:10:04.200 --> 1:10:06.985
♪ ♪

1:10:21.826 --> 1:10:23.349
Come what may.

1:10:23.480 --> 1:10:26.178
[dramatic music plays]

1:10:26.352 --> 1:10:29.137
♪ ♪

1:10:40.932 --> 1:10:43.717
[dramatic music plays]

1:10:43.804 --> 1:10:46.590
♪ ♪
